The Colosseum, built by the FLAVIANS (though it was technically done by Titus, Domitian just modified it, sorry Bee)
The Colosseum was used for gladiatorial contests and public spectacles such as mock sea battles, animal hunts, executions, re-enactments of famous battles, and dramas based on Classical mythology.

The Colosseum ceased to be used for entertainment in the early medieval era. It was later reused for such purposes as housing, workshops, quarters for a religious order, a fortress, a quarry, and a Christian shrine.
The Colosseum was built on top of an artificial lake built by Nero outside his Domus Aurea. Take that Nero!
The construction was largely funded by spoils taken from the Temple of Jerusalem. So yeah, that sucks.

Just three graceful columns stand of this very ancient building, the Temple of Castor and Pollux (Tempio dei Dioscuri), the twins. Legend tells these heroes (the sons of Jupiter and Leda) appeared on this spot to help the forces of the Roman Republic overcome the last king of Rome.

The roman amphitheater in Volterra.  In the Middle Ages the theatre was reduced by the construction of the defensive wall in the 13th century so that the summa cavea and the entrance to the theatre are no longer visible.

The roman amphitheater in Volterra. The Theatre was commissioned by two members of the CAECINAE family, Aulo Caecina Severo and Gaio Caecina Largo, both Roman consuls, the former in the 1st century B.C. and the latter in the 42 A.D

The roman amphitheater in Volterra. The cavea, or the seating area was built into a natural incline like Greek theatres and is composed of two tiers of steps: the ima cavea with 10 rows of seats in Pignano limestone and the media cavea with 9 rows of seats in the same stone.
